Q: fix blocking issue when trying to parse HTTP request in java A: <p>The issue you're encountering is a classic HTTP parsing problem... When your buffer is large enough to read the entire request in one go, <code>input.read(buffer)</code> successfully reads all the data, but then the loop continues and calls <code>read()</code> again. Since the client (curl) has sent everything and is waiting for a response, your server blocks waiting for more data that will never come.</p>
<p>One of clean solution is to ensure your <code>request</code> object properly tracks:</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Whether headers are complete (found <code>\r\n\r\n</code>)</p>
</li>
<li><p>Whether a body is expected (check <code>Content-Length</code> or <code>Transfer-Encoding</code> headers)</p>
</li>
<li><p>How many body bytes have been received vs. expected</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>Then simply don't call <code>read()</code> again once <code>isDone()</code> returns true:</p>
<pre class="lang-java prettyprint-override"><code>byte[] buffer = new byte[1024];
int offset = 0;

while(!request.isDone()) {
    int n = input.read(buffer, offset, buffer.length - offset);
    if(n == -1) break;

    // parseRequest now returns how many bytes it consumed
    int consumed = request.parseRequest(buffer, offset + n);

    if(request.isDone()) {
        // Preserve unconsumed bytes for next request
        int remaining = (offset + n) - consumed;
        if(remaining &gt; 0) {
            System.arraycopy(buffer, consumed, buffer, 0, remaining);
        }
        offset = remaining;
        break;
    }

    offset = 0;
}
</code></pre>
<p>For a GET request like your curl example, there's no request body, so once you've parsed the headers (ending with <code>\r\n\r\n</code>), your <code>isDone()</code> should return <code>true</code> and you should exit the loop immediately.</p>
<p><strong>The key insight:</strong> You need to detect completion from the HTTP protocol itself, not from the socket closing or blocking.</p>
<p><em>Thanks to @Remy Lebeau for pointing out the importance of handling pipelined requests and preserving unconsumed bytes.</em></p>
